	  <title>Examples of Position Vectors</title>
	  <caption>Position Vectors - Examples</caption>
	  <example>
		    <statement.example>
			      <para>
            <para.body>The position vector of the point <math>
                  <latex>X(3,1)</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
               </math> is <math>
                  <latex>\mathbf{x}=(3,1)</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <para align="center">
            <para.body>
				           <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img src="PositionVector.gif"/>
               </media>
			         </para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.example>
		    <answer type="Explanation" version="1">
         <answer.block>
            <answer.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Indeed, the arrow joining the origin to <math>
                        <latex>X</latex>
                     </math> goes, starting from its tail, <math>
                        <latex>3</latex>
                     </math> units in the first coordinate direction and from there <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math> unit in the second coordinate direction. The corresponding coordinate vector is <math>
                        <latex>\mathbf{x}=(3,1)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.block.body>
         </answer.block>
      </answer>
	  </example>
	  <example>
		    <statement.example>
			      <para>
            <para.body>The point <math>
                  <latex>X(7,-5,2)</latex>
               </math> in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
               </math> has the position vector <math>
                  <latex>\mathbf{x} = (7,-5,2).</latex>
               </math>
			         </para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.example>
		    <answer type="Explanation" version="1">
         <answer.block>
            <answer.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The position vector <math>
                        <latex>\mathbf{x}</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>X</latex>
                     </math> is represented by the arrow whose tail is at the origin and whose tip is at <math>
                        <latex>X</latex>
                     </math>. Therefore <math>
                        <latex>\mathbf{x}=(7,-5,2)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.block.body>
         </answer.block>
      </answer>
	  </example>
	  <example>
		    <statement.example>
			      <para>
            <para.body>
				           <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
               </math> has four basic coordinate vectors</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.example>
		    <answer type="Explanation" version="1">
         <answer.block>
            <answer.block.body>
			            <ul>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>The first basic coordinate vector of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                           </math> is <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{e}_1:=(1,0,0,0)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>The second basic coordinate vector of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                           </math> is <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{e}_2:=(0,1,0,0)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>The third basic basic coordinate vector of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                           </math> is <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{e}_3:=(0,0,1,0)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>The fourth basic basic coordinate vector of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                           </math> is <math>
                              <latex>\mathbf{e}_4:=(0,0,0,1)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
			            </ul>
		          </answer.block.body>
         </answer.block>
      </answer>
	  </example>
</example.pack>
